00:30:22.510 --> 00:30:25.330
But then more recently, a
lot more noticeable strides.

00:30:25.330 --> 00:30:29.097
And then Joss Whedon
has LGBTQ characters.

00:30:29.097 --> 00:30:31.180
And then, of course, the
Marvel Cinematic Universe

00:30:31.180 --> 00:30:32.974
with Black Panther
and Luke Cage.

00:30:32.974 --> 00:30:34.390
A.D. JAMESON:
Slowly coming along.

00:30:34.390 --> 00:30:35.931
JOSH PYLE: Yeah,
slowly coming along.

00:30:35.931 --> 00:30:38.030
It's taken a few years.

00:30:38.030 --> 00:30:40.990
And part of that adds more
complexity to storytelling,

00:30:40.990 --> 00:30:41.500
too.

00:30:41.500 --> 00:30:44.650
Because just acknowledging that,
thinking about Black Panther,

00:30:44.650 --> 00:30:48.790
for example, the complexity of
a character like Killmonger,

00:30:48.790 --> 00:30:52.049
very complex, a lot
of different things

00:30:52.049 --> 00:30:54.340
you're processing when you're
seeing that battle that's

00:30:54.340 --> 00:30:57.247
happening and some of
things he talked about.

00:30:57.247 --> 00:30:59.830
But it seems that there's some
backlash also that's happening.

00:30:59.830 --> 00:31:02.170
And especially I think it's
very noticeable with "Star

00:31:02.170 --> 00:31:05.700
Wars," like "The Last Jedi"
being an example of that.

00:31:05.700 --> 00:31:07.390
Tell us a little
more about your take

00:31:07.390 --> 00:31:11.400
on that and why it is that a
certain semblance of geeks,

00:31:11.400 --> 00:31:13.240
predominantly white
males, let's face it,

00:31:13.240 --> 00:31:15.437
are having a struggle
a bit with this change.

00:31:15.437 --> 00:31:17.020
A.D. JAMESON: Yeah,
so I mean, there's

00:31:17.020 --> 00:31:18.395
a couple of things
going on here.

00:31:18.395 --> 00:31:20.670
The first, of course,
is in pop culture,

00:31:20.670 --> 00:31:23.000
just the politics of our
moment are obviously greatly--

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:26.860
we're living through
a period where--

00:31:26.860 --> 00:31:29.560
you can think that there's
always different politics

00:31:29.560 --> 00:31:30.310
in the culture.

00:31:30.310 --> 00:31:33.520
But there's times
in our culture where

00:31:33.520 --> 00:31:37.750
maybe politics are a little
more monolithic and top-down.

00:31:37.750 --> 00:31:40.360
And at least people
publicly pretend

00:31:40.360 --> 00:31:41.810
to agree on the same things.

00:31:41.810 --> 00:31:44.826
And there's other parts
and other periods where

00:31:44.826 --> 00:31:47.200
there are just conflicting
views that are both mainstream

00:31:47.200 --> 00:31:48.899
and people are battling on.

00:31:48.899 --> 00:31:51.190
We're clearly in one of those
latter moments right now.

00:31:51.190 --> 00:31:53.314
So everything is
politicized these days,

00:31:53.314 --> 00:31:54.730
and so we would
expect pop culture

00:31:54.730 --> 00:31:57.250
and geek culture to be
politicized as well.

00:31:57.250 --> 00:32:00.010
But I think another
thing that's happening

00:32:00.010 --> 00:32:05.110
is-- so this growth in geek
culture and its mainstreaming

00:32:05.110 --> 00:32:07.760
is really being driven
more than anything

00:32:07.760 --> 00:32:11.080
else I think by fans themselves
and by geeks themselves.

00:32:11.080 --> 00:32:12.910
Corporations are
coming in and trying

00:32:12.910 --> 00:32:17.140
to actually monetize it and
figure out how to make money

00:32:17.140 --> 00:32:18.320
off the demographic.

00:32:18.320 --> 00:32:21.510
But remember, there were "Star
Trek" fans making their own fan

00:32:21.510 --> 00:32:24.700
fiction before they figured
out how to make those novels.

00:32:24.700 --> 00:32:29.951
And the geeks were making "Star
Wars" products before Lucas--

00:32:29.951 --> 00:32:32.200
the corporations are kind
of falling behind and coming

00:32:32.200 --> 00:32:36.430
in and trying to figure out
how to actually corporatize it.

00:32:36.430 --> 00:32:38.530
And of course, as more
and more money flows in,

00:32:38.530 --> 00:32:40.613
it becomes more and more
mainstream, more visible,

00:32:40.613 --> 00:32:41.330
more public.

00:32:41.330 --> 00:32:44.770
But if you think about the kind
of people geeks tend to be,

00:32:44.770 --> 00:32:47.890
the way I describe geeks in the
book-- and anybody can be geek.

00:32:47.890 --> 00:32:51.430
If anybody wants to say, I'm a
geek, you're a geek, whatever.

00:32:51.430 --> 00:32:52.492
It's not like there's a--

00:32:52.492 --> 00:32:54.700
you don't need a membership
card or something, right?

00:32:54.700 --> 00:32:56.680
But traditionally
what geeks are are

00:32:56.680 --> 00:33:00.500
people who tend to be interested
in two things at the same time.

00:33:00.500 --> 00:33:04.120
They tend to like
fantasy of any kind.

00:33:04.120 --> 00:33:06.430
It could be
animation or puppets,

00:33:06.430 --> 00:33:08.140
or it could be science fiction.

00:33:08.140 --> 00:33:09.040
It could be horror.

00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:10.490
It could be any of these things.

00:33:10.490 --> 00:33:13.919
But then they also tend to
be more technically minded.

00:33:13.919 --> 00:33:16.210
And they tend to be interested
in the STEM disciplines.

00:33:16.210 --> 00:33:17.709
They like the
sciences, whether it's

00:33:17.709 --> 00:33:20.920
the hard sciences or the
more social sciences, math,

00:33:20.920 --> 00:33:23.140
engineering,
computers, whatever.

00:33:23.140 --> 00:33:24.640
And what they
particularly like is

00:33:24.640 --> 00:33:27.080
to see the intersection
of those two things.

00:33:27.080 --> 00:33:29.390
So there are people who
are interested in fantasy

00:33:29.390 --> 00:33:32.210
but aren't interested in
seeing a scientific version

00:33:32.210 --> 00:33:32.710
of fantasy.

00:33:32.710 --> 00:33:35.037
They want to see a
crazy, irrational.

00:33:35.037 --> 00:33:36.620
So like someone like
David Lynch would

00:33:36.620 --> 00:33:37.900
be a good example of that.

00:33:37.900 --> 00:33:39.220
He likes fantasy.

00:33:39.220 --> 00:33:40.340
He likes the supernatural.

00:33:40.340 --> 00:33:43.015
But he likes it to be
mysterious and weird and more

00:33:43.015 --> 00:33:45.320
like a nightmare or something.

00:33:45.320 --> 00:33:47.390
What geeks tend to do
is they kind of come in.

00:33:47.390 --> 00:33:49.681
They're interested in fantasy,
but what they want to do

00:33:49.681 --> 00:33:51.340
is they want to treat
the supernatural

00:33:51.340 --> 00:33:52.990
as an extension of the natural.

00:33:52.990 --> 00:33:56.560
They want to actually figure
out what the scientific laws are

00:33:56.560 --> 00:34:00.845
or the biological, like
what's the history of elves

00:34:00.845 --> 00:34:03.220
or what's their culture like,
what's their language like.

00:34:03.220 --> 00:34:05.230
And so they begin
to kind of take

00:34:05.230 --> 00:34:06.730
the supernatural
and the fantastical

00:34:06.730 --> 00:34:10.584
and bring it in under rational,
empirical methodologies

00:34:10.584 --> 00:34:13.000
and tools and frameworks and
try to actually understand it

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:13.699
that way.

00:34:13.699 --> 00:34:16.570
So it's this intersection of
the STEM disciplines and fantasy

00:34:16.570 --> 00:34:19.960
I think that traditionally
is what defines a geek.

00:34:19.960 --> 00:34:22.170
So if you think
about it that way,

00:34:22.170 --> 00:34:25.630
you've always had people of
all different walks of life

00:34:25.630 --> 00:34:27.350
being interested in fantasy.

00:34:27.350 --> 00:34:30.443
But the STEM disciplines in
particular, traditionally were,

00:34:30.443 --> 00:34:32.609
if you go back historically,
if we go back and think

00:34:32.609 --> 00:34:36.820
to the 1960s, 1970s,
1980s, it tended

00:34:36.820 --> 00:34:41.110
to be a whiter male discipline
for various reasons.

00:34:41.110 --> 00:34:43.750
My mom in high school was
really interested in science.

00:34:43.750 --> 00:34:45.250
She wanted to be a
marine biologist,

00:34:45.250 --> 00:34:47.124
and she was told when
she was in high school,

00:34:47.124 --> 00:34:49.239
you can't be that,
you can't do that.

00:34:49.239 --> 00:34:50.850
You should be an
English major instead

00:34:50.850 --> 00:34:52.600
or you should become
a nurse or something.

00:34:52.600 --> 00:34:54.850
So she didn't become
a marine biologist.

00:34:54.850 --> 00:34:57.520
Hopefully that attitude
has changed today.

00:34:57.520 --> 00:35:01.400
And as the STEM disciplines
and tech job and things

00:35:01.400 --> 00:35:04.400
like that are themselves
diversifying, which

00:35:04.400 --> 00:35:06.530
is long overdue,
of course, you're

00:35:06.530 --> 00:35:11.700
seeing geek culture
also diversify and grow.

00:35:11.700 --> 00:35:13.690
And again, that's
something I think

00:35:13.690 --> 00:35:15.900
that's being driven by
the fans themselves.

00:35:15.900 --> 00:35:17.570
And so the companies
are a little slower

00:35:17.570 --> 00:35:18.800
to pick up on this.

00:35:18.800 --> 00:35:20.130
But again, they're cautious.

00:35:20.130 --> 00:35:22.712
They're trying to figure out
how to safely monetize this.

00:35:22.712 --> 00:35:25.170
In terms of a backlash, I think
part of what you're seeing,

00:35:25.170 --> 00:35:28.520
of course, is that for a long
time a certain group of people

00:35:28.520 --> 00:35:33.590
perceived geek culture as
being their underground niche.

00:35:33.590 --> 00:35:35.160
And I think it's two things.

00:35:35.160 --> 00:35:36.760
I think, one, is
a lot of geeks are

00:35:36.760 --> 00:35:38.510
kind of resentful to
see it go mainstream.

00:35:38.510 --> 00:35:40.635
The same way if you're a
fan of an underground band

00:35:40.635 --> 00:35:42.718
and then you see them go
mainstream, on some level

00:35:42.718 --> 00:35:45.050
you feel like maybe
you've lost something.

00:35:45.050 --> 00:35:45.680
You haven't.

00:35:45.680 --> 00:35:47.100
Pop culture belongs
to everybody,

00:35:47.100 --> 00:35:49.558
and you can still go back and
listen to the earlier albums.

00:35:49.558 --> 00:35:52.700
But look, when I was growing
up, I loved "X-Men" comics.

00:35:52.700 --> 00:35:55.370
And I suffered from this myself.

00:35:55.370 --> 00:35:58.610
When I saw them making the
"X-Men" movies in 1999, 2000,

00:35:58.610 --> 00:36:01.550
on some level, I felt
resentful about it.

00:36:01.550 --> 00:36:03.149
Because it wasn't
the "X-Men" I knew.

00:36:03.149 --> 00:36:04.940
I was like, look, it
looks at the "Matrix."

00:36:04.940 --> 00:36:06.840
They're wearing black
leather jumpsuits.

00:36:06.840 --> 00:36:08.630
They're using Wire Fu.

00:36:08.630 --> 00:36:10.460
That's not the "X-Men."

00:36:10.460 --> 00:36:12.500
When I was reading
it in 1986 and they

00:36:12.500 --> 00:36:14.780
were in the Australian
Outback and the team

00:36:14.780 --> 00:36:18.930
was Longshaw, Rogue,
Dazzler, Wolverine, Colossus,

00:36:18.930 --> 00:36:21.714
it's like Havoc, Storm,
that's the X-Men.

00:36:21.714 --> 00:36:23.630
I don't want to see--
they're changing things.

00:36:23.630 --> 00:36:24.350
So I get it.

00:36:24.350 --> 00:36:28.280
I felt like it wasn't
exactly what I wanted.

00:36:28.280 --> 00:36:29.630
But here's the thing.

00:36:29.630 --> 00:36:31.910
I was reading "X-Men" in 1986.

00:36:31.910 --> 00:36:35.801
There were "X-Men" fans in 1976.

00:36:35.801 --> 00:36:38.300
I was the new kid on the block
who looked obnoxious to them.

00:36:38.300 --> 00:36:40.174
Like what are you talking
about 1986 "X-Men?"

00:36:40.174 --> 00:36:41.390
It's not the 1976 "X-Men."

00:36:41.390 --> 00:36:43.987
Then you have the 1966 "X-Men"
fans, who are like, wait, wait,

00:36:43.987 --> 00:36:44.570
wait a minute.

00:36:44.570 --> 00:36:45.070
Hold on.

00:36:45.070 --> 00:36:46.071
We were here first.

00:36:46.071 --> 00:36:48.570
The thing about pop culture is
that it belongs to everybody.

00:36:48.570 --> 00:36:49.486
And it keeps evolving.

00:36:49.486 --> 00:36:51.110
And it has to keep evolving.

00:36:51.110 --> 00:36:55.610
And it keeps going in the
direction of our own interests.

00:36:55.610 --> 00:36:58.754
I write in the book that pop
culture characters don't die.

00:36:58.754 --> 00:36:59.420
They don't live.

00:36:59.420 --> 00:37:00.046
They don't die.

00:37:00.046 --> 00:37:02.586
The thing that happens to them
is that we might lose interest

00:37:02.586 --> 00:37:03.390
in them.

00:37:03.390 --> 00:37:06.110
So if you look at a franchise,
like a character like Dick

00:37:06.110 --> 00:37:11.100
Tracy right now, Dick
Tracy seems to me--

00:37:11.100 --> 00:37:13.370
if people even
remember Dick Tracy.

00:37:13.370 --> 00:37:15.590
There's not much action
happening on the Dick Tracy

00:37:15.590 --> 00:37:16.280
front, right?

00:37:16.280 --> 00:37:17.660
There was the
movie back in 1990.

00:37:17.660 --> 00:37:20.750
I guess the cartoon, the
comic is still being made.

00:37:20.750 --> 00:37:23.511
Does he still talk into
the wrist radio thing?

00:37:23.511 --> 00:37:25.510
There's probably some
Dick Tracy fans out there.

00:37:25.510 --> 00:37:28.190
They're probably mostly
over the age of 40,

00:37:28.190 --> 00:37:29.810
maybe over the age of 60.

00:37:29.810 --> 00:37:31.520
And if you're going
to make something

00:37:31.520 --> 00:37:33.230
that appeals to
people today, you

00:37:33.230 --> 00:37:35.070
have to update it
to the present day.

00:37:35.070 --> 00:37:37.747
So I think the smarter--

00:37:37.747 --> 00:37:39.830
so some of what the "Star
Wars" franchise has done

00:37:39.830 --> 00:37:43.160
is like, yeah, like
the time it was made,

00:37:43.160 --> 00:37:44.930
there were way too
many guys in it.

00:37:44.930 --> 00:37:46.571
It's overwhelmingly white.

00:37:46.571 --> 00:37:49.070
If you want to update it today
and you want to actually make

00:37:49.070 --> 00:37:53.210
it appeal to the people who
are the geeks today, absolutely

00:37:53.210 --> 00:37:54.630
it should be much more diverse.

00:37:54.630 --> 00:37:59.780
And I think it's a
confluence of these things.

00:37:59.780 --> 00:38:02.870
As the geek
industries themselves

00:38:02.870 --> 00:38:05.840
diversify as it becomes
more mainstream, as our pop

00:38:05.840 --> 00:38:09.010
culture fights out
these political battles,

00:38:09.010 --> 00:38:10.880
you're going to see
those trends continue.

00:38:10.880 --> 00:38:14.510
So the two things I think we can
say about geek culture is, one,

00:38:14.510 --> 00:38:17.409
I don't think we're
anywhere near--

00:38:17.409 --> 00:38:19.700
as big as it is now, it's
going to keep getting bigger.

00:38:19.700 --> 00:38:22.550
And then, two, I
think also the side

00:38:22.550 --> 00:38:26.120
is totally on the side of
greater diversity and all

00:38:26.120 --> 00:38:27.460
those things in geek culture.

00:38:27.460 --> 00:38:29.293
That part seems to be
taking a bit of-- that

00:38:29.293 --> 00:38:31.160
seems to be lagging
behind a bit more.

00:38:31.160 --> 00:38:33.440
I think 2014, 2016
have kind of been

00:38:33.440 --> 00:38:36.196
inflection points with Gamergate
and then the election of Trump.

00:38:36.196 --> 00:38:38.570
I think a lot of these things
have bubbled to the surface

00:38:38.570 --> 00:38:39.945
and really broke
through in a way

00:38:39.945 --> 00:38:41.660
and created
visibility for forces

00:38:41.660 --> 00:38:45.734
that people weren't paying
attention to before that.

00:38:45.734 --> 00:38:47.900
JOSH PYLE: So we have just
a couple of minutes left.

00:38:47.900 --> 00:38:51.120
In just a minute, we're
going to open up for Q&amp;A. So

00:38:51.120 --> 00:38:52.370
be thinking of your questions.

00:38:52.370 --> 00:38:55.530
And the microphone is
just right over there.

00:38:55.530 --> 00:38:58.250
So be thinking about that.

00:38:58.250 --> 00:39:02.310
We only have time probably
for one question from me.

00:39:02.310 --> 00:39:06.062
So I'm thinking
from the list here.

00:39:06.062 --> 00:39:08.270
So let's talk about diverse
experiences a little bit.

00:39:08.270 --> 00:39:09.811
So in the book, you
talk a little bit

00:39:09.811 --> 00:39:12.810
of how you'd love to experience
the "Star Trek" holodeck.

00:39:12.810 --> 00:39:17.630
And I think you also mentioned
in the book about holodeck

00:39:17.630 --> 00:39:19.052
addiction, right?

00:39:19.052 --> 00:39:20.510
But the point I'm
really getting to

00:39:20.510 --> 00:39:24.050
is around new technologies and
the use of new technologies.

00:39:24.050 --> 00:39:25.747
We could go on a
lot of territory

00:39:25.747 --> 00:39:27.830
here, but the use of
technology for storytelling--

00:39:27.830 --> 00:39:29.240
I think that's
where I would like

00:39:29.240 --> 00:39:33.470
to get your opinions for
emerging storytellers,

00:39:33.470 --> 00:39:36.020
people who are thinking
about world-building,

00:39:36.020 --> 00:39:38.304
who know that they
have to create rich,

00:39:38.304 --> 00:39:40.220
dense stories if they're
going to be the Harry

00:39:40.220 --> 00:39:42.760
Potter of 10 years from now.

00:39:42.760 --> 00:39:45.619
A.D. JAMESON: Yeah, so I
mentioned that the way I define

00:39:45.619 --> 00:39:46.910
a geek in the book are people--

00:39:46.910 --> 00:39:49.410
it's again this intersection
between people who like fantasy

00:39:49.410 --> 00:39:53.180
and the supernatural, whatever
that entails, and then try

00:39:53.180 --> 00:39:56.540
to bring a more
technical or scientific

00:39:56.540 --> 00:39:58.647
or engineering based
mindset to bear upon it.

00:39:58.647 --> 00:40:00.730
And they want to see the
intersection of those two

00:40:00.730 --> 00:40:01.780
things.

00:40:01.780 --> 00:40:05.507
That's a large part of why
geeks like realism, is because

00:40:05.507 --> 00:40:07.090
in a lot of ways,
what they want to do

00:40:07.090 --> 00:40:09.790
is they want to produce this
sense that the other world

00:40:09.790 --> 00:40:12.130
actually exists as much
as possible, like we

00:40:12.130 --> 00:40:14.080
saw with the role-playing game.

00:40:14.080 --> 00:40:16.960
So any kind of technology
that allows them to do that,

00:40:16.960 --> 00:40:19.960
if you think about it--
a movie is a technology

00:40:19.960 --> 00:40:21.070
for having a fantasy.

00:40:21.070 --> 00:40:22.990
A book is a technology
for having a fantasy.

00:40:22.990 --> 00:40:24.130
A comic book is that.

00:40:24.130 --> 00:40:28.390
And I think a lot of geeks,
what they're driven then to do

00:40:28.390 --> 00:40:31.224
is to try to create
immersive experiences that

00:40:31.224 --> 00:40:32.890
allow them to actually
feel like they're

00:40:32.890 --> 00:40:38.217
living in that other world
and having that experience.

00:40:38.217 --> 00:40:39.550
They want it to be as complete--

00:40:39.550 --> 00:40:40.924
you want to actually
be in there,

00:40:40.924 --> 00:40:42.430
and you want to
be able to believe

00:40:42.430 --> 00:40:45.070
you're actually in that world
and forgot that you were--

00:40:45.070 --> 00:40:46.541
I mean, I know I do.

00:40:46.541 --> 00:40:48.040
I would like more
than anything else

00:40:48.040 --> 00:40:49.930
to go live on the
Starship Enterprise.

00:40:49.930 --> 00:40:51.720
It seems like a much
better place than--

00:40:51.720 --> 00:40:54.015
and particularly the Next
Generation Enterprise.

00:40:54.015 --> 00:40:55.390
It just seems like
a better place

00:40:55.390 --> 00:40:57.880
than a lot of where
we currently live.

00:40:57.880 --> 00:40:59.410
I'd love to live in that world.

00:40:59.410 --> 00:41:02.292
So if somebody actually could
build a replica of the Starship

00:41:02.292 --> 00:41:04.750
Enterprise, and I could actually
just go walk around in it,

00:41:04.750 --> 00:41:06.989
that would be my
life's dream come true.

00:41:06.989 --> 00:41:09.280
It's like the best I'm going
to get if I can't actually

00:41:09.280 --> 00:41:11.950
go live in that world.

00:41:11.950 --> 00:41:14.436
If somebody creates
a virtual reality

00:41:14.436 --> 00:41:17.060
headset, where I could actually
experience that, I'd love that.

00:41:17.060 --> 00:41:18.730
And I think one of the
things you're seeing,

00:41:18.730 --> 00:41:20.770
people are trying to do
that with VR and stuff.

00:41:20.770 --> 00:41:23.920
But one of the more
recent evolutions,

00:41:23.920 --> 00:41:27.490
and I'm not surprised by this,
is the creation of theme parks

00:41:27.490 --> 00:41:30.967
that are modeled around
particular brands,

00:41:30.967 --> 00:41:32.800
so like the Wizarding
World of Harry Potter,

00:41:32.800 --> 00:41:35.410
where you go in,
you got the wand,

00:41:35.410 --> 00:41:37.240
you can actually
interact with things.

00:41:37.240 --> 00:41:39.190
Again, it's like you're
going to Hogwarts.

00:41:39.190 --> 00:41:40.640
It's like this
amazing experience.

00:41:40.640 --> 00:41:41.620
They're doing it with "Avatar."

00:41:41.620 --> 00:41:43.036
They're doing it
with "Star Wars."

00:41:43.036 --> 00:41:46.090
So I think, again, they're
trying to figure out,

00:41:46.090 --> 00:41:48.190
because they have this
demographic, how they can

00:41:48.190 --> 00:41:51.130
create that
experience for people

00:41:51.130 --> 00:41:53.057
who will go and
will spend-- like I

00:41:53.057 --> 00:41:54.140
want this particular wand.

00:41:54.140 --> 00:41:56.680
I will spend $80 on it
and have that experience.

00:41:56.680 --> 00:41:58.600
So yeah, from any tech--

00:41:58.600 --> 00:42:01.390
it could be VR, it
could be 3D movies,

00:42:01.390 --> 00:42:04.060
it could be video games.

00:42:04.060 --> 00:42:06.670
It could be just
building the things.

00:42:06.670 --> 00:42:09.587
People like to build
replicas of things and stuff.

00:42:09.587 --> 00:42:11.170
But to have that
immersive experience.

00:42:11.170 --> 00:42:14.130
JOSH PYLE: Yeah,
immersive, real, lived in.

00:42:14.130 --> 00:42:15.796
A.D. JAMESON: Yeah,
a realist-- yeah, it

00:42:15.796 --> 00:42:17.400
should look like an actual
other world you've gone to.

00:42:17.400 --> 00:42:18.110
JOSH PYLE: Yeah.

00:42:18.110 --> 00:42:19.320
A.D. JAMESON: Yeah.

00:42:19.320 --> 00:42:21.352
It's like my cell phone
screen is cracked,

00:42:21.352 --> 00:42:23.560
so why shouldn't the droids
have some scuffs on them.

00:42:23.560 --> 00:42:26.290
That's what the real
world looks like.

00:42:26.290 --> 00:42:28.584
We get hurt, so our
characters should get hurt.

00:42:28.584 --> 00:42:29.250
JOSH PYLE: Yeah.

00:42:29.250 --> 00:42:30.430
It's true.

00:42:30.430 --> 00:42:33.020
All right, so we have
time for a few questions.

00:42:33.020 --> 00:42:34.460
The microphone is over there.

00:42:34.460 --> 00:42:37.903
So feel free to
step up to the mic.

00:42:37.903 --> 00:42:38.444
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:42:38.444 --> 00:42:41.180
Thank you for coming
to talk to us.

00:42:41.180 --> 00:42:45.200
I actually was an English
major and a fantasy nerd.

00:42:45.200 --> 00:42:47.900
But I was a Victorianist,
so I definitely

00:42:47.900 --> 00:42:51.560
identify with your high and low
concept in literary criticism

00:42:51.560 --> 00:42:52.110
idea.

00:42:52.110 --> 00:42:53.840
And so my undergraduate
dissertation

00:42:53.840 --> 00:42:58.890
was on Jacques Derrida's concept
of the archive, fan fiction,

00:42:58.890 --> 00:43:00.597
copyright, and Tolkien.

00:43:00.597 --> 00:43:01.730
A.D. JAMESON: Wow, good.

00:43:01.730 --> 00:43:06.440
AUDIENCE: And the Tolkien
estate was very, very anti

00:43:06.440 --> 00:43:12.530
the fandom participating
in and extending the--

00:43:12.530 --> 00:43:16.200
basically he went after a
lot of copyright issues.

00:43:16.200 --> 00:43:17.972
And I've watched
that kind of evolve,

00:43:17.972 --> 00:43:19.430
and I'm very curious
what you think

00:43:19.430 --> 00:43:23.870
about how fandoms are kind
of appropriating things,

00:43:23.870 --> 00:43:26.750
continuing to expand
universes, and then

00:43:26.750 --> 00:43:29.840
that fight between
what's canon, what's not,

00:43:29.840 --> 00:43:34.357
where they step on copyright
issues, these sorts of issues

00:43:34.357 --> 00:43:35.940
that you're getting
to talk about now.

00:43:35.940 --> 00:43:39.050
A.D. JAMESON: Yeah, I have a
background in Victorian studies

00:43:39.050 --> 00:43:41.830
myself, too.

00:43:41.830 --> 00:43:46.370
And actually, it's related,
because the Victorians had--

00:43:46.370 --> 00:43:48.526
you see an explosion
of literacy and reading

00:43:48.526 --> 00:43:49.400
in Victorian culture.

00:43:49.400 --> 00:43:52.550
And to this day, one of the
conflicts in Victorian studies

00:43:52.550 --> 00:43:54.620
is like, what are the
actual works of literature?

00:43:54.620 --> 00:43:56.420
What are the more
genre [INAUDIBLE]..

00:43:56.420 --> 00:43:59.210
So that's part of the
relationship, my interest

00:43:59.210 --> 00:44:01.670
in those two things.

00:44:01.670 --> 00:44:04.790
Yeah, the Tolkien estate is
a funny one, because they--

00:44:04.790 --> 00:44:08.300
when they first
approached Tolkien

00:44:08.300 --> 00:44:10.137
like in the '60s about
making a movie out

00:44:10.137 --> 00:44:11.720
of "The Lord of the
Rings," they could

00:44:11.720 --> 00:44:15.140
see it was growing in
popularity, among especially

00:44:15.140 --> 00:44:17.840
young people, hippies.

00:44:17.840 --> 00:44:21.380
And his agent said to him, well,
do you want them to do this?

00:44:21.380 --> 00:44:26.790
And Tolkien said
one of two things.

00:44:26.790 --> 00:44:28.930
If they won't give
me any money for it,

00:44:28.930 --> 00:44:30.950
then we should
insist on high art,

00:44:30.950 --> 00:44:32.690
like it should be a great film.

00:44:32.690 --> 00:44:33.650
But if they'll give
me a lot of money,

00:44:33.650 --> 00:44:35.025
then I don't care
what they make.

00:44:35.025 --> 00:44:36.840
[LAUGHS] It was like
one or the other.

00:44:36.840 --> 00:44:38.780
And they actually ended
up selling the rights,

00:44:38.780 --> 00:44:41.120
and then the rights-- there's
a really interesting book

00:44:41.120 --> 00:44:47.650
on this called "The Frodo
Franchise" by Kristin Thompson,

00:44:47.650 --> 00:44:51.860
where she went through the whole
history of how the rights were

00:44:51.860 --> 00:44:54.170
caught up in legal battles
and why really the movie is

00:44:54.170 --> 00:44:55.940
in some ways, besides
the animated versions,

00:44:55.940 --> 00:44:57.315
didn't really end
up getting made

00:44:57.315 --> 00:45:00.170
until the late 90s, early 2000s.

00:45:00.170 --> 00:45:02.780
But yeah, the Tolkien
estate, though,

00:45:02.780 --> 00:45:05.480
has tried to control
in a lot of ways.

00:45:05.480 --> 00:45:08.060
And they don't like the
Peter Jackson movies.

00:45:08.060 --> 00:45:11.700
And they're like, you're never
making "The Silmarillion," et

00:45:11.700 --> 00:45:12.550
cetera, et cetera.

00:45:12.550 --> 00:45:14.870
And they also claim they
never got any of the money

00:45:14.870 --> 00:45:16.590
from it and stuff.

00:45:16.590 --> 00:45:18.700
But the thing about
it is I understand

00:45:18.700 --> 00:45:20.324
that if you're talking
about officially

00:45:20.324 --> 00:45:21.890
licensed Tolkien
stuff, but at point,

00:45:21.890 --> 00:45:23.360
the copyright will run out.

00:45:23.360 --> 00:45:26.600
But I'm a real firm
believer that pop culture

00:45:26.600 --> 00:45:27.530
belongs to everybody.

00:45:27.530 --> 00:45:29.390
Anyone who's interested
in it, anybody

00:45:29.390 --> 00:45:31.370
who reads it and has a--

00:45:31.370 --> 00:45:35.362
when I was a kid, I loved
Lloyd Alexander novels,

00:45:35.362 --> 00:45:36.320
the Prydain Chronicles.

00:45:36.320 --> 00:45:38.190
They were some of the first
books I fell in love with.

00:45:38.190 --> 00:45:40.606
They made a Disney film, "The
Black Caldron," out of them.

00:45:40.606 --> 00:45:42.470
They're supposedly
trying to make a TV show.

00:45:42.470 --> 00:45:44.389
And I sat there, and I wrote--

00:45:44.389 --> 00:45:46.430
like those books end if
you get to the fifth one.

00:45:46.430 --> 00:45:47.120
They end.

00:45:47.120 --> 00:45:50.910
But I wrote Prydain Chronicles,
Lloyd Alexander fan fiction.

00:45:50.910 --> 00:45:54.560
And I imagined myself into
the stories and meeting

00:45:54.560 --> 00:45:58.120
Taran and Eilonwy and Hen Wen,
all those characters and stuff.

00:45:58.120 --> 00:45:59.870
And you can't stop
people from doing that.

00:45:59.870 --> 00:46:03.320
I don't see why
anybody would want to.

00:46:03.320 --> 00:46:06.140
Now, I think the question then
becomes, anybody can do that,

00:46:06.140 --> 00:46:10.030
but then if other
people like it,

00:46:10.030 --> 00:46:12.020
it will go on and have
a life outside that.

00:46:12.020 --> 00:46:14.310
If you want to write your
own "Star Wars" fan fiction,

00:46:14.310 --> 00:46:15.980
you can do that, or your
own "Lord of the Rings" fan

00:46:15.980 --> 00:46:16.580
fiction.

00:46:16.580 --> 00:46:21.050
But it doesn't mean anybody else
is going to want to read it.

00:46:21.050 --> 00:46:24.140
But the things that people
like will go on and become

00:46:24.140 --> 00:46:29.480
fan favorites and maybe will
eventually get picked up

00:46:29.480 --> 00:46:31.080
by these companies, I think.

00:46:31.080 --> 00:46:33.230
I think they're actually
foolish if they ignore

00:46:33.230 --> 00:46:37.220
those segments of the fan base.

00:46:37.220 --> 00:46:40.820
Like with "Star Wars," it's
like Mara Jade is clearly

00:46:40.820 --> 00:46:43.070
a beloved character in
the Star Wars universe.

00:46:43.070 --> 00:46:45.400
Why they have not introduced
her into the [INAUDIBLE],,

00:46:45.400 --> 00:46:46.900
I just think that's
foolish of them.

00:46:46.900 --> 00:46:48.330
They should, that kind of thing.

00:46:48.330 --> 00:46:49.910
And similarly, if
there's somebody--

00:46:49.910 --> 00:46:52.430
I'm not quite as up on
Tolkien fan fiction,

00:46:52.430 --> 00:46:53.900
but if there's
somebody out there

00:46:53.900 --> 00:46:55.610
who's writing really good
Tolkien fan fiction and people

00:46:55.610 --> 00:46:57.470
like it, I think they
should look to that

00:46:57.470 --> 00:46:59.270
and maybe try to
adopt it or something.

00:46:59.270 --> 00:47:00.645
AUDIENCE: I always
thought it was

00:47:00.645 --> 00:47:02.061
really interesting
because Tolkien

00:47:02.061 --> 00:47:05.200
himself was such a scholar
of Norwegian mythology,

00:47:05.200 --> 00:47:06.020
Greek mythology.

00:47:06.020 --> 00:47:07.490
He was basically
ripping off a lot

00:47:07.490 --> 00:47:11.330
of archival, universal
stuff anyway.

00:47:11.330 --> 00:47:13.190
So I thought it was
a bit hypocritical.

00:47:13.190 --> 00:47:16.250
A.D. JAMESON: Oh, yeah, like
the stuff comes from "Beowulf."

00:47:16.250 --> 00:47:18.860
It comes from the
"Nibelungen," it's

00:47:18.860 --> 00:47:22.640
like he took stuff
left and right.

00:47:22.640 --> 00:47:24.480
I mean, culture
belongs to everybody.

00:47:28.749 --> 00:47:29.670
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:47:29.670 --> 00:47:31.630
Thanks for coming.

00:47:31.630 --> 00:47:33.590
I'm just wondering in
your definition of geek

00:47:33.590 --> 00:47:36.550
and focusing on people who
are interested in STEM,

00:47:36.550 --> 00:47:40.120
it seems to exclude a large
portion of the mainstream

00:47:40.120 --> 00:47:41.495
people who might
identify as geek

00:47:41.495 --> 00:47:42.790
and are starting to--
like the kind of people

00:47:42.790 --> 00:47:44.706
who are really excited
about "Big Bang Theory"

00:47:44.706 --> 00:47:46.260
or you mentioned "Harry Potter."

00:47:46.260 --> 00:47:48.720
How do you see those
two worlds intersecting?

00:47:48.720 --> 00:47:50.840
Where's the middle there?

00:47:50.840 --> 00:47:54.260
There's certainly people who
travel in between those worlds.

00:47:54.260 --> 00:47:55.610
What's in the middle?

00:47:55.610 --> 00:47:57.692
A.D. JAMESON: Yeah,
I do define "geek"

00:47:57.692 --> 00:47:58.900
a particular way in the book.

00:47:58.900 --> 00:48:01.350
And in a lot of ways,
what the book is about

00:48:01.350 --> 00:48:03.610
is the past 40 years
of geek culture.

00:48:03.610 --> 00:48:07.180
It's kind of how we've had
40 years of "Star Wars" now.

00:48:07.180 --> 00:48:09.370
How did the "Star
Wars" franchise

00:48:09.370 --> 00:48:12.310
grow up and change
in those 40 years?

00:48:12.310 --> 00:48:15.380
And how did geek culture change
during that time period, too?

00:48:15.380 --> 00:48:17.070
And it's changed a lot.

00:48:17.070 --> 00:48:19.992
And it's going to keep changing.

00:48:19.992 --> 00:48:21.950
One of the things that
is happening, of course,

00:48:21.950 --> 00:48:25.130
is that as it becomes
more mainstream,

00:48:25.130 --> 00:48:27.530
the definition of it is
becoming a lot more diffuse.

00:48:27.530 --> 00:48:29.500
And that's just an
inevitable-- again,

00:48:29.500 --> 00:48:31.083
it's not that different
from something

00:48:31.083 --> 00:48:32.290
like punk going mainstream.

00:48:32.290 --> 00:48:34.331
Punk music is something
I'm really interested in.

00:48:34.331 --> 00:48:37.952
And if you go back
in time to 1976, who

00:48:37.952 --> 00:48:40.410
would identify as a punk or
being interested in punk music?

00:48:40.410 --> 00:48:42.266
It's a very specialized thing.

00:48:42.266 --> 00:48:43.390
Because it is a subculture.

00:48:43.390 --> 00:48:44.740
It's a small culture.

00:48:44.740 --> 00:48:46.780
Even by the time you
get to 1978, 1979,

00:48:46.780 --> 00:48:49.660
what counts as punk music
was already really diffuse.

00:48:49.660 --> 00:48:54.330
And nowadays, what counts as
that is all over the place.

00:48:54.330 --> 00:48:57.312
So there's nothing to stop that.

00:48:57.312 --> 00:48:59.770
And I don't even think it's a
thing that should be stopped.

00:48:59.770 --> 00:49:01.780
As geek culture goes
mainstream, you're

00:49:01.780 --> 00:49:04.030
going to see something that
maybe was more of a highly

00:49:04.030 --> 00:49:08.495
specialized term or it was
more specific in a couple

00:49:08.495 --> 00:49:10.120
of different identities
it referred to.

00:49:10.120 --> 00:49:11.650
But it's going to expand.

00:49:11.650 --> 00:49:14.920
And so, yeah, I think
you have very casual geek

00:49:14.920 --> 00:49:17.080
fans these days.

00:49:17.080 --> 00:49:18.880
That's how it is.

00:49:18.880 --> 00:49:22.676
I mean, in a lot of ways, people
who are like hardcore geeks

00:49:22.676 --> 00:49:24.550
and stuff should be
really grateful for that.

00:49:24.550 --> 00:49:29.467
Because if it were
just the geeks,

00:49:29.467 --> 00:49:31.300
like if you go back in
time, how many people

00:49:31.300 --> 00:49:36.010
would have shown up to watch an
"Avengers" movie in like 1975?

00:49:36.010 --> 00:49:37.810
It probably wouldn't
have made any money.

00:49:37.810 --> 00:49:39.709
So they wouldn't have
been able to make it.

00:49:39.709 --> 00:49:42.250
If you liked "Infinity War," if
you like the Marvel Cinematic

00:49:42.250 --> 00:49:44.694
Universe, if you
liked the fact--

00:49:44.694 --> 00:49:46.860
the fact that "Infinity
War" just crossed $2 billion

00:49:46.860 --> 00:49:49.840
globally, the only way it can
do that is if a lot of people

00:49:49.840 --> 00:49:50.590
beyond--

00:49:50.590 --> 00:49:53.027
there's a lot more geeks
now than there used to be.

00:49:53.027 --> 00:49:54.610
But even if all the
geeks in the world

00:49:54.610 --> 00:49:56.530
showed up and saw
it like 10 times,

00:49:56.530 --> 00:49:59.020
it still wouldn't make
$2 billion globally.

00:49:59.020 --> 00:50:00.230
It wouldn't even come close.

00:50:00.230 --> 00:50:02.650
So there's a lot of people
who are more casual fans who

00:50:02.650 --> 00:50:03.740
are showing up as well.

00:50:03.740 --> 00:50:07.150
And look, if they want to say
they're geeks, like whatever.

00:50:07.150 --> 00:50:08.260
They're geeks.

00:50:08.260 --> 00:50:11.284
I mean, I think of it
more as a spectrum.

00:50:11.284 --> 00:50:12.700
On one level, it's
like people who

00:50:12.700 --> 00:50:16.310
are just kind of like the most
casual fans you can imagine.

00:50:16.310 --> 00:50:19.427
And then at the other end, you
have the most die-hard fans

00:50:19.427 --> 00:50:21.760
who know every single thing
and are completely obsessed.

00:50:21.760 --> 00:50:24.180
And I'm not even
at that end myself.

00:50:24.180 --> 00:50:25.180
I don't know where I am.

00:50:25.180 --> 00:50:26.346
I'm someone on the spectrum.

00:50:26.346 --> 00:50:29.710
I'm probably closer to
the more enfranchised end.

00:50:29.710 --> 00:50:32.740
But maybe it's only like 75%.

00:50:32.740 --> 00:50:34.240
Trust me, in writing
this book, I've

00:50:34.240 --> 00:50:35.860
met people who are
far more into it

00:50:35.860 --> 00:50:39.050
than I am and are
far more into it.

00:50:39.050 --> 00:50:43.480
I know people who all they wear
at home is a Starfleet uniform.

00:50:43.480 --> 00:50:44.740
So it's like, that's great.

00:50:44.740 --> 00:50:46.740
And then on the other
hand, you have some people

00:50:46.740 --> 00:50:48.430
who just want to go to
Target and buy a T-shirt,

00:50:48.430 --> 00:50:49.221
and they're a geek.

00:50:49.221 --> 00:50:51.030
And that's-- you know.

00:50:51.030 --> 00:50:52.870
But that's the sign
that it's going

00:50:52.870 --> 00:50:54.520
mainstream, the fact that--

00:50:54.520 --> 00:50:56.260
I think it's in many
ways a lovely thing

00:50:56.260 --> 00:50:59.650
that it's something that's
more accessible to people

00:50:59.650 --> 00:51:02.311
and they can choose their
level of engagement with it.

00:51:02.311 --> 00:51:03.310
Its doesn't have to be--

00:51:03.310 --> 00:51:05.360
because it used to be like
if you wanted to read--

00:51:05.360 --> 00:51:07.360
again, I go back to "X-Men"
comics in the '80s, but if you

00:51:07.360 --> 00:51:09.609
wanted to read these things,
it was hard to find them.

00:51:09.609 --> 00:51:13.640
And I'm happier now that they're
accessible to more people.

00:51:13.640 --> 00:51:15.710
So does that answer
the question?

00:51:15.710 --> 00:51:17.156
AUDIENCE: Yeah, thanks.

00:51:17.156 --> 00:51:19.564
I also selfishly
appreciate that it's

00:51:19.564 --> 00:51:22.230
going more mainstream, because I
think it encourages more gender

00:51:22.230 --> 00:51:22.990
diversity.

00:51:22.990 --> 00:51:25.990
A.D. JAMESON: Yeah, totally.

