How do you tie that in?

00:51:46.850 --> 00:51:48.726
A.D. JAMESON: Yeah, so
when I wrote the book,

00:51:48.726 --> 00:51:51.058
I was just calling it "Star
Wars and the Triumph of Geek

00:51:51.058 --> 00:51:51.660
Culture."

00:51:51.660 --> 00:51:53.160
And my publisher
said to me, we have

00:51:53.160 --> 00:51:54.890
to have a thing to
put in front of that.

00:51:54.890 --> 00:51:56.390
And I said--

00:51:56.390 --> 00:51:57.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:57.020 --> 00:51:57.794
I said, well, why?

00:51:57.794 --> 00:51:59.210
And they said,
because we have to.

00:51:59.210 --> 00:52:00.410
And I said, OK.

00:52:00.410 --> 00:52:02.190
So I mean, that
was their decision.

00:52:02.190 --> 00:52:05.669
So then they said to me, they
said, we want to call it--

00:52:05.669 --> 00:52:06.710
what was it they wanted--

00:52:06.710 --> 00:52:08.411
they said, we want to call it--

00:52:08.411 --> 00:52:09.984
oh, man, I wish I
could think of it.

00:52:09.984 --> 00:52:12.400
They had another line from
"Star Wars" they wanted to use.

00:52:12.400 --> 00:52:13.880
And it was terrible.

00:52:13.880 --> 00:52:16.340
Because it sounded like I
was insulting geek culture.

00:52:16.340 --> 00:52:19.284
It will come back
to me what it was.

00:52:19.284 --> 00:52:21.200
Oh, it was, "I Have a
Bad Feeling About This--

00:52:21.200 --> 00:52:22.160
Star Wars and the
Triumph of Geek Culture."

00:52:22.160 --> 00:52:23.542
And I said, first
of all, I said,

00:52:23.542 --> 00:52:26.000
that's like the biggest "Star
Wars" cliche you can possibly

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:27.030
imagine.

00:52:27.030 --> 00:52:29.000
And I said, it's also
just completely wrong.

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:30.060
I love my publisher.

00:52:30.060 --> 00:52:31.040
FSG is a great press.

00:52:31.040 --> 00:52:32.665
They're a bit more
of a literary press.

00:52:32.665 --> 00:52:34.940
They're not so much a geekier--

00:52:34.940 --> 00:52:38.120
even like the science
fiction stuff they do,

00:52:38.120 --> 00:52:40.070
they tend to do things
like the Southern Reach

00:52:40.070 --> 00:52:40.820
trilogy and stuff.

00:52:40.820 --> 00:52:42.320
So it's a little
more like literary.

00:52:42.320 --> 00:52:44.278
They want to call it
speculative fiction stuff.

00:52:44.278 --> 00:52:48.327
So anyway, I said, no, no,
no, that's completely wrong.

00:52:48.327 --> 00:52:50.160
So then I was like, OK,
I'm on the hook now.

00:52:50.160 --> 00:52:52.050
I better come up with a better
expression, a better line

00:52:52.050 --> 00:52:53.633
from "Star Wars" or
else they're going

00:52:53.633 --> 00:52:55.067
to completely ruin this book.

00:52:55.067 --> 00:52:57.150
And you should have seen
the cover they originally

00:52:57.150 --> 00:52:57.670
wanted to put on this, too.

00:52:57.670 --> 00:53:00.660
It was like this sad, emo Darth
Vader like crying or something.

00:53:00.660 --> 00:53:02.920
I was like, guys, you're
not marketing this book

00:53:02.920 --> 00:53:03.420
to hipsters.

00:53:03.420 --> 00:53:04.628
You're marketing it to geeks.

00:53:04.628 --> 00:53:05.560
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:05.560 --> 00:53:08.301
So, and there's an intersection
between geeks and hipsters,

00:53:08.301 --> 00:53:08.800
too.

00:53:08.800 --> 00:53:10.620
But I said, this is
a book for geeks.

00:53:10.620 --> 00:53:12.631
And so this book is a
defense of geek culture,

00:53:12.631 --> 00:53:13.880
like I want to defend what's--

00:53:13.880 --> 00:53:15.480
there's plenty of
books and articles

00:53:15.480 --> 00:53:17.190
out there telling you what's
wrong with geek culture.

00:53:17.190 --> 00:53:18.606
This is a defense
of geek culture,

00:53:18.606 --> 00:53:21.450
and it's a defense of
it on artistic grounds,

00:53:21.450 --> 00:53:22.937
moral grounds, cultural grounds.

00:53:22.937 --> 00:53:25.020
It's like a full-throated
defense of geek culture.

00:53:25.020 --> 00:53:29.410
So I said, well,
how about this one?

00:53:29.410 --> 00:53:31.246
I actually went through.

00:53:31.246 --> 00:53:32.620
I just watched
"Star Wars" again.

00:53:32.620 --> 00:53:34.420
I wrote down anything that could
possibly be a title in front of

00:53:34.420 --> 00:53:35.380
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:35.380 --> 00:53:36.797
And finally I went,
OK, how about,

00:53:36.797 --> 00:53:38.421
"I find your lack of
faith disturbing,"

00:53:38.421 --> 00:53:40.630
because I thought that
one works because it means

00:53:40.630 --> 00:53:41.810
two different things, right?

00:53:41.810 --> 00:53:43.030
Like it's true.

00:53:43.030 --> 00:53:45.460
If you're a geek, on some
level, when you meet non-geeks,

00:53:45.460 --> 00:53:47.876
especially if you find out
those non-geeks are going to be

00:53:47.876 --> 00:53:50.740
in charge of making the new
"Star Wars" movie or the new--

00:53:50.740 --> 00:53:51.760
you get scared.

00:53:51.760 --> 00:53:54.220
Because you find their
lack of faith disturbing.

00:53:54.220 --> 00:53:56.890
It's like you don't want them
to be in charge of making--

00:53:56.890 --> 00:53:58.640
the best example would
be like Michael Bay

00:53:58.640 --> 00:53:59.920
making the "Transformers"
movies, right?

00:53:59.920 --> 00:54:02.529
A lot of people who are geeks
hate the "Transformers" movies

00:54:02.529 --> 00:54:03.820
because they're not very geeky.

00:54:03.820 --> 00:54:07.120
And so when Michael Bay was
going make "Turtles" movies,

00:54:07.120 --> 00:54:08.470
people get scared, right?

00:54:08.470 --> 00:54:10.330
So there's that.

00:54:10.330 --> 00:54:12.760
You want to find out instead
that people you trust

00:54:12.760 --> 00:54:14.802
and who are fellow geeks
are making these things.

00:54:14.802 --> 00:54:16.468
But at the same time,
I think the people

00:54:16.468 --> 00:54:18.040
who are outside
geek culture, there

00:54:18.040 --> 00:54:19.270
is something a little like--

00:54:19.270 --> 00:54:24.130
it looks a bit maybe like a
cult or a religion or something.

00:54:24.130 --> 00:54:26.620
So it kind of goes both ways.

00:54:26.620 --> 00:54:28.450
It is like these geeks--

00:54:28.450 --> 00:54:30.280
and again, that's from
my own experience.

00:54:30.280 --> 00:54:33.460
I remember being 15
years old, 14 years old

00:54:33.460 --> 00:54:35.260
and going over to
my friends' houses

00:54:35.260 --> 00:54:38.394
and talking to their parents
about the "Princess Bride"

00:54:38.394 --> 00:54:40.810
and why they should watch it
and probably talking about it

00:54:40.810 --> 00:54:43.240
for like an hour and them
being like, why is he just

00:54:43.240 --> 00:54:48.160
talking about this, this movie
and this book for like an hour?

00:54:48.160 --> 00:54:48.940
It's crazy.

00:54:48.940 --> 00:54:49.630
It's absurd.

00:54:49.630 --> 00:54:51.770
So yeah, it kind of
cuts both ways, I think.

00:54:51.770 --> 00:54:54.760
So I wanted to get that
duality in the title,

00:54:54.760 --> 00:54:57.040
if that makes sense.

00:54:57.040 --> 00:54:59.164
But they made me put
something on the front.

00:54:59.164 --> 00:55:00.830
I wouldn't have thought
of it on my own.

00:55:00.830 --> 00:55:01.330
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:01.330 --> 00:55:03.487
That's a market
force at work on me.

00:55:03.487 --> 00:55:05.320
I don't know why they
had to have the title,

00:55:05.320 --> 00:55:08.692
but they say it sells better
if you have the title.

00:55:08.692 --> 00:55:11.150
Although now they refer to it
as "I Find Your Lack of Faith

00:55:11.150 --> 00:55:12.500
Disturbing," and
I'm like, I'd rather

00:55:12.500 --> 00:55:14.100
call it "Star Wars and
Triumph of Geek Culture."

00:55:14.100 --> 00:55:15.808
That gets more to what
the book is about.

00:55:15.808 --> 00:55:20.430
But they keep calling it "I Find
Your Lack of Faith Disturbing."

